1
00:00:01,559 --> 00:00:06,689
What we’re searching for?
What everyone is searching for?

2
00:00:06,699 --> 00:00:15,499
Actual love, affection which, 
when that general concept is refined

3
00:00:15,499 --> 00:00:19,799
and expressed purely, 
it’s prem or Kṛṣṇa-prem.

4
00:00:19,799 --> 00:00:21,636
It’s not a thing of this world.

5
00:00:21,686 --> 00:00:26,270
[Love Is not a Thing of This World]

6
00:00:26,270 --> 00:00:29,850
Love means prem, 
means Kṛṣṇa-prem,

7
00:00:29,850 --> 00:00:32,090
they’re synonymous.

8
00:00:32,090 --> 00:00:38,570
There’s not one love here, 
and Kṛṣṇa-prem is another love.

9
00:00:38,587 --> 00:00:43,247
Love means Kṛṣṇa-prem.

10
00:00:43,260 --> 00:00:47,390
Accept no substitute.

11
00:00:48,924 --> 00:00:54,094
When Śrīla Prabhupād put it this way
in one of his purports in Bhagavad-gītā,

12
00:00:54,094 --> 00:01:01,755
he said, “When our natural propensity
for love, meaning this Kṛṣṇa-prem,

13
00:01:01,755 --> 00:01:06,026
when it’s perverted,

14
00:01:06,026 --> 00:01:11,006
it’s expressed 
as lust towards matter.”

15
00:01:11,666 --> 00:01:18,226
Which is similar to a statement
in Caitanya-caritāmṛta , as

16
00:01:18,226 --> 00:01:22,856
kāma andha-tamaḥ, prema nirmala bhāskara 
[Cc: 1.4.171]

17
00:01:22,856 --> 00:01:27,636
Kām, which is the word for ‘lust’.

18
00:01:27,636 --> 00:01:33,776
Andha-tamaḥ means 
‘the dense dark ignorance’.

19
00:01:33,776 --> 00:01:40,920
Prem nirmala bhāskar—
it’s like pure sunshine.

20
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:43,270
Or Guru Mahārāj said once,

21
00:01:43,270 --> 00:01:46,910
“Dense light … 
dense darkness—dense light.”

22
00:01:46,910 --> 00:01:50,426
kāma andha-tamaḥ, prema nirmala bhāskara 
 

23
00:01:50,426 --> 00:01:56,506
Guru Mahārāj compared
to North Pole and South Pole,

24
00:01:56,506 --> 00:02:04,226
meaning—on a superficial glance, 
observation

25
00:02:04,226 --> 00:02:10,307
we notice that they look similar—
North Pole, South Pole.

26
00:02:10,307 --> 00:02:15,747
Saying, but he’s invoking this

27
00:02:15,763 --> 00:02:17,343
(try to whisper)

28
00:02:17,343 --> 00:02:25,313
he’s invoking this metaphor
to tell us: but they’re worlds apart

29
00:02:25,323 --> 00:02:28,643
like night and day—
North Pole, South Pole.

30
00:02:28,643 --> 00:02:32,023
So, appear to be similar,
but are worlds apart.

31
00:02:32,023 --> 00:02:36,583
So, the love, the so-called love
of this world

32
00:02:36,583 --> 00:02:44,743
it appears to be similar to divine love, 
but they’re worlds apart.

33
00:02:44,763 --> 00:02:48,130
ātmendriya-prīti-vāñchā—tāre bali ‘kāma’

34
00:02:48,130 --> 00:02:52,780
kṛṣṇendriya-prīti-icchā dhare ‘prema’ nāma 
[Cc: 1.4.165]

35
00:02:52,780 --> 00:02:56,055
Again, it’s mentioned 
in Caitanya-caritāmṛta :

36
00:02:56,055 --> 00:03:08,755
ātmendriya—that trying
to have everything egocentric,

37
00:03:08,765 --> 00:03:19,715
when our goal is the satisfaction 
of our own senses,

38
00:03:19,715 --> 00:03:23,715
seeing an egocentric world
that everything is meant

39
00:03:23,715 --> 00:03:26,715
for our pleasure, satisfaction,

40
00:03:26,715 --> 00:03:31,495
that we’re taking ourselves 
to be the centre of all existence—

41
00:03:31,515 --> 00:03:33,635
that’s called kām.

42
00:03:33,635 --> 00:03:37,595
kṛṣṇendriya-prīti-icchā dhare ‘prema’ nāma
[Cc: 1.4.165]

43
00:03:37,595 --> 00:03:41,691
But reconfiguring oneself, 
redirecting oneself

44
00:03:41,691 --> 00:03:45,281
towards the Absolute centre,

45
00:03:45,911 --> 00:03:52,621
hṛṣīkeṇa hṛṣīkeśa-sevanaṁ bhaktir ucyate
[Nārada-pañcarātra]

46
00:03:52,621 --> 00:03:57,900
of dedicating ourselves 
and our acquired energy

47
00:03:57,900 --> 00:04:01,824
in the service 
the senses of Kṛṣṇa,

48
00:04:01,824 --> 00:04:05,416
saying, this caused 
by the name of prem.

